    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's a good start. i think it'll help them understand the impact. i'm also worried about students asking why this is some kind of \"essential\" way to read the constitution rather than just focusing on the actual legal procedures. how should i explain to them why the substantive side is more important for justice than just the procedural side?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is essential because it ensures that the government doesn't just follow fair procedures, but also respects and protects fundamental rights that are crucial for a just society. Focusing solely on procedural due process would allow the government to technically follow the rules but still infringe on basic human rights, like privacy, freedom of speech, and equality. By emphasizing substantive due process, we make sure that the Constitution isn't just a set of rules for how laws are made and enforced, but a living document that upholds the core values of liberty and justice. This approach prevents the government from overstepping its bounds and ensures that individual freedoms are not sacrificed for the sake of procedural correctness. It's about making sure that the spirit of the Constitution, which is to protect and empower individuals, isn't lost in a maze of legal technicalities.",
      "source": "target",
